WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.840
Yeah, hello.

00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:07.840
It's great to be here.

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:09.320
My name is Klaus Wilke.

00:00:09.320 --> 00:00:14.800
I'm with the University of Texas at Austin, and today I'm talking about work that has

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:18.040
been sponsored by the R Consortium.

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:23.240
That's why they're prominently featured in the bottom, and it's about improving text

00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:25.240
rendering in ggplot.

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:31.959
So a common problem that probably all of you at some point have run into is you may want

00:00:31.959 --> 00:00:35.500
to mix italics and normal text in ggplot.

00:00:35.500 --> 00:00:40.919
So in my day work, I'm a biologist, so it's a very common problem for biologists.

00:00:40.919 --> 00:00:45.320
You have species names that are supposed to be in italics, but then you have other text

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:47.939
surrounding it that shouldn't be in italics.

00:00:47.939 --> 00:00:50.020
So how can we make that happen?

00:00:50.020 --> 00:00:56.560
And so just to give you an example of how that may arise, here's a stack overflow issue

00:00:56.560 --> 00:00:58.900
that's asking that question.

00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:03.740
For my plot figure, I want to label categories on a bar plot with the first word being italicized

00:01:03.740 --> 00:01:06.739
while the following words are not italicized.

00:01:06.739 --> 00:01:11.500
I want the category labels to look as follows, and so there's a typical biology example.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:13.139
There's a bacterial name.

00:01:13.139 --> 00:01:19.180
I'm not trying to pronounce it, and then OTU1, operational taxonomic unit.

00:01:19.339 --> 00:01:23.019
That's a biology term, but in any case, so this should be italics.

00:01:23.019 --> 00:01:26.260
This should not be italics, right?

00:01:26.260 --> 00:01:32.320
So let's look a little more into the example code and data that comes with this issue.

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:36.559
So this is a made-up data set that the person provided.

00:01:36.559 --> 00:01:40.440
We have in the first column the name of the bacterial species.

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:42.580
Then we have these OTUs.

00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:47.720
Then we have a name column that combines the bacterial species and the OTUs, and then we

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:54.760
have some numeric value, and so the person was turning this into a bar plot with just

00:01:54.760 --> 00:01:56.339
three lines of ggplot, right?

00:01:56.339 --> 00:02:03.300
You take the data, pipe it into ggplot, put name on x and value on y, but then we flip

00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:07.720
the coordinates so we get a horizontal plot, and of course, you see the problem in this

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:11.860
plot is that the bacterial names are not in italics.

00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:13.839
So how can we solve that problem?

00:02:14.100 --> 00:02:20.360
The common solution that you will find for that is some sort of plot math.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:24.039
So this is the accepted solution on Stack Overflow.

00:02:24.039 --> 00:02:29.339
You can make a vector of expressions and apply it to the labels argument in scale x discrete,

00:02:29.339 --> 00:02:35.660
and so the code that makes the magic happen is this code here, quote italic parenthesis

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:41.139
single quote double quote comma x bracket one.

00:02:41.139 --> 00:02:42.860
I cannot write that code.

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:48.559
I'm sure there's people in this room who can write that code, and I salute you.

00:02:48.559 --> 00:02:53.399
I cannot, and I don't want to.

00:02:53.399 --> 00:03:04.479
I would rather write my own text rendering software in C++, and so that's what I've done.

00:03:04.479 --> 00:03:12.039
Okay, so that leads us to the question, so how should we specify formatted text?

00:03:12.039 --> 00:03:15.460
So let's make first a slightly simple example.

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:19.500
Instead of the axis tick label, let's just look at the title.

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:21.860
Okay, I want a title.

00:03:21.860 --> 00:03:26.639
Species names are in italics, and italics should be in italics, and maybe I've already

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:30.820
given it away, so I put italics and stars.

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:34.300
Anybody that has used Markdown knows this, right?

00:03:34.300 --> 00:03:40.380
If you're using R Markdown, if you want something in italics, you put stars around it, and so

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:44.479
that's what this package ggtext facilitates.

00:03:44.479 --> 00:03:47.419
So as of right now, it's still in development.

00:03:47.419 --> 00:03:52.479
You have to install it from GitHub, but it's essentially ready to go.

00:03:52.479 --> 00:03:57.240
It's just waiting for the next release of ggplot, so sometime within the next two to

00:03:57.240 --> 00:03:59.539
three months, this should be on CRAN.

00:03:59.539 --> 00:04:01.800
So I've now loaded the package.

00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:06.399
Nothing has happened yet because I haven't changed anything in the code.

00:04:06.399 --> 00:04:11.820
It wouldn't be good if just randomly stars were interpreted as Markdown because maybe

00:04:11.820 --> 00:04:15.179
sometimes you actually want to have stars in your text.

00:04:15.179 --> 00:04:20.059
So we have to tell ggplot that now it should interpret this as Markdown, and so I've hooked

00:04:20.059 --> 00:04:27.100
this up with the theme system so that now if you've ever used themes in ggplot, usually

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:34.500
the plot.title tells us how the title of the plot is styled, and normally you would write

00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:38.480
element text, and then you can use that to change the color and so on.

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:42.839
And now I've written this element Markdown, and so now you see this has been interpreted

00:04:42.839 --> 00:04:47.839
as Markdown, and so now this initalics is initalics.

00:04:47.839 --> 00:04:53.760
Okay, so now let's apply this to the original problem.

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:59.519
So the additional issue here now is that we have these different species names, and we

00:04:59.519 --> 00:05:02.440
don't want to manually put them into stars.

00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:04.359
We want to automate that, right?

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:09.940
And so there, a really, really good companion package is the glue package.

00:05:09.940 --> 00:05:14.339
If you're not routinely using glue, I encourage you to look into it.

00:05:14.339 --> 00:05:22.359
Glue allows you to very quickly paste pieces from your data frame into strings of text.

00:05:22.359 --> 00:05:30.260
So I'm taking the data here, pipe into mutate, and then I create a new name column where

00:05:30.260 --> 00:05:36.220
I call glue, and then here I have this star, and then backed name is the column name that

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:42.500
has the bacterial name in curly braces, and that tells glue, don't write backed name into

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:45.100
the string, but actually pull it from the data frame.

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:49.899
And then here, the same with OTU name, and so that now creates this table where now you

00:05:49.899 --> 00:05:54.059
see I have nice stars around the bacterial names.

00:05:54.059 --> 00:05:58.059
And so now I pipe this into ggplot with the element Markdown.

00:05:58.059 --> 00:06:06.079
So now it's, of course, the axis.text.y that I want to change, and now you see this is

00:06:06.079 --> 00:06:08.380
in italics.

00:06:08.380 --> 00:06:11.380
This is not.

00:06:11.380 --> 00:06:19.100
Okay, I see this solves a problem.

00:06:19.100 --> 00:06:24.459
Okay, so now you might say, okay, your plots are boring.

00:06:24.459 --> 00:06:26.380
Don't you ever use color?

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:27.380
I do.

00:06:27.700 --> 00:06:28.700
I do.

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:31.899
So let's do something with color.

00:06:31.899 --> 00:06:36.779
Let's actually, let's add a color column.

00:06:36.779 --> 00:06:41.899
I'm doing a little bit of a trick, so if Hadley's not in the room, right, he would say, you're

00:06:41.899 --> 00:06:43.980
circumventing the scale system.

00:06:43.980 --> 00:06:46.380
Yes, in this case, that's the right way to do it.

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:55.619
So I'm adding a color vector, so these are just colors that I chose, and now I'm still

00:06:55.619 --> 00:07:01.299
using glue, but now you may see here I'm actually writing a little bit of HTML.

00:07:01.299 --> 00:07:09.500
So this is the italics tag now, and I'm using inline CSS styling to get the color in there.

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:20.179
And with that, I can actually have now colors.

00:07:20.179 --> 00:07:25.059
So the trick that I'm using here is I'm using scale fill identity, so I'm mapping color

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:30.700
onto fill, and then scale fill identity instead of trying to set up a color mapping.

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:34.579
It just takes the actual colors that are in the column.

00:07:34.579 --> 00:07:39.779
Now one other thing that you may notice, it's a topic that's very dear to my heart.

00:07:39.779 --> 00:07:46.160
You may notice that visually these colors and these colors look kind of the same, right?

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:51.739
They match very well, but I'm actually setting the transparency to 0.5 here.

00:07:51.739 --> 00:07:59.299
So the bars are actually at 50% transparency, and then they look the same as the text, which

00:07:59.299 --> 00:08:01.940
is completely opaque.

00:08:01.940 --> 00:08:04.220
And that's just how our visual system works.

00:08:04.220 --> 00:08:08.500
When you color large areas, you need the color to be lighter.

00:08:08.500 --> 00:08:13.459
It's a very common problem that I see when people color text, that the text becomes too

00:08:13.459 --> 00:08:14.459
light.

00:08:14.459 --> 00:08:20.859
Like the text always needs to use a darker color to look the same as a large area that

00:08:20.859 --> 00:08:22.899
you colored the same.

00:08:22.899 --> 00:08:24.579
So this worked out well.

00:08:24.579 --> 00:08:29.820
So if you make the color 50% transparent, it's going to be about right.

00:08:29.820 --> 00:08:37.039
Okay, so now we're getting ambitious, right?

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:39.380
What else can I do?

00:08:39.380 --> 00:08:41.780
So this is another issue from stack overflow.

00:08:41.780 --> 00:08:43.539
It's another biological problem.

00:08:43.539 --> 00:08:46.059
So it's made up data.

00:08:46.059 --> 00:08:48.739
The key thing here is there are these phases.

00:08:48.739 --> 00:08:53.140
So these are phases of cell division, again, a biological example.

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:55.900
And so this person had these different images.

00:08:55.900 --> 00:09:00.260
And so this image corresponds to this phase, this image corresponds to this phase, and

00:09:00.260 --> 00:09:01.260
so on.

00:09:01.260 --> 00:09:06.859
And so the question was, can we somehow get the images into the figure?

00:09:06.859 --> 00:09:08.900
And we can.

00:09:08.900 --> 00:09:11.859
So now we're using the image tag.

00:09:11.859 --> 00:09:15.200
We're loading or we're setting the images.

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:20.679
So in this particular case, it's in a folder on my hard drive, but you can pull them from

00:09:20.679 --> 00:09:22.039
a web page if you want.

00:09:22.039 --> 00:09:23.039
That works just fine.

00:09:23.039 --> 00:09:28.280
We put a break tag, and then the word, and we stick it into ggplot.

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:30.359
The only other thing is line height.

00:09:30.359 --> 00:09:33.520
The default line height, for some reason, is just too low.

00:09:33.520 --> 00:09:34.520
It's 0.9.

00:09:34.520 --> 00:09:35.520
I don't know why.

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:40.880
1.2 is a better line height if you actually want to have things in two lines.

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:42.039
And there we go.

00:09:42.039 --> 00:09:53.919
We have the images in the axis and the label underneath.

00:09:53.919 --> 00:09:56.159
I see this solves another problem.

00:09:56.159 --> 00:09:58.159
Very good.

00:09:58.159 --> 00:10:02.159
There's a few other things that it can do.

00:10:02.159 --> 00:10:07.880
So there's actually the option to have text boxes with some amount of text wrapping.

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:13.080
You can color the background.

00:10:13.080 --> 00:10:18.239
If you go to the website, which is in the bottom right corner, you can see the code

00:10:18.239 --> 00:10:21.799
that makes this particular figure.

00:10:21.799 --> 00:10:26.000
So everything I've shown so far is theme elements.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:27.640
Does this only work for theme elements?

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:28.640
No.

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:34.640
I also have written a geom that you can use to use the same text rendering in a plot.

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:37.400
So let's do another common situation.

00:10:37.919 --> 00:10:41.239
This is the iris data set, which I assume everybody knows.

00:10:41.239 --> 00:10:44.679
So we have three species of iris flowers.

00:10:44.679 --> 00:10:49.000
We're plotting the sepal width against the sepal length for the three species.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.159
And we are putting regression lines in here.

00:10:52.159 --> 00:10:59.039
And so oftentimes, when you have a plot like that, you may want to annotate this with,

00:10:59.039 --> 00:11:02.739
say, the R squared of the regression line.

00:11:02.739 --> 00:11:08.419
And so it's, again, the problem, OK, how do I get the R squared into some plot math

00:11:08.419 --> 00:11:12.820
expression that then I can add to the plot?

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:17.380
And so we'll, instead of doing that, use the same technique here.

00:11:17.380 --> 00:11:19.700
So let's just go through the code quickly.

00:11:19.700 --> 00:11:22.520
So first, we calculate the correlation.

00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:27.619
So we take the iris data set, group by species, summarize, calculate the R squared.

00:11:27.619 --> 00:11:33.299
So then we end up with a table that has the species names and the R squared, right?

00:11:33.299 --> 00:11:36.979
And now, we turn this into our labels.

00:11:36.979 --> 00:11:41.340
So this sepal length and sepal width, 8 and 4.5, those are just the coordinates where

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:43.299
the label will appear in the plot.

00:11:43.299 --> 00:11:45.419
And then, again, I use the glue function.

00:11:45.419 --> 00:11:48.179
So I have R in stars.

00:11:48.179 --> 00:11:53.119
So it's going to be italics, superscript 2, because it's going to be R squared.

00:11:53.119 --> 00:11:57.719
And here, I'm pasting in the correlation coefficient, and I round it to two digits.

00:11:57.719 --> 00:12:03.239
So in the glue package, inside the square brackets, you can just write regular R code,

00:12:03.239 --> 00:12:07.320
and it gets executed and replaced by the resulting string.

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:16.479
And then, this goes into ggplot, into a geom rich text, which takes the label and interprets

00:12:16.479 --> 00:12:18.520
it as HTML.

00:12:18.599 --> 00:12:24.239
And so now, you have here this label, R squared equals whatever.

00:12:24.239 --> 00:12:28.320
So by default, it puts a white background and a box around it.

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:29.640
But all of that, you can change.

00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:31.640
You can take the box away if you want.

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:34.840
You can put a different background and so on.

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:37.719
So that's really all I can do.

00:12:37.719 --> 00:12:41.440
However, there's actually two packages that I've written.

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:48.679
So this package was the ggtext package, which provides the interface to ggplot.

00:12:48.679 --> 00:12:52.080
But it's really just a wrapper around an underlying package.

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:54.500
So the package that makes it all possible.

00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:56.679
And that already is on CRAN.

00:12:56.679 --> 00:12:59.799
And that's the grid text package.

00:12:59.799 --> 00:13:05.159
And so that is a great package if you're actually writing grid graphics code.

00:13:05.159 --> 00:13:08.960
So for example, if you're writing your own ggplot extensions.

00:13:08.960 --> 00:13:14.919
And I've made it so that if you're used to writing grid code, it should be very easy

00:13:14.919 --> 00:13:16.520
to use the grid text package.

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:20.080
So if you've never seen grid code, this may look scary.

00:13:20.080 --> 00:13:22.719
But if you have seen grid code, this should be very familiar.

00:13:22.719 --> 00:13:26.599
So this is, so far, just regular grid.

00:13:26.599 --> 00:13:29.059
I have some text here.

00:13:29.059 --> 00:13:33.320
Then I set up grid graphics parameters, so GPAR graphics parameters.

00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:37.580
I'm using a silly font with some font size and a color.

00:13:37.580 --> 00:13:44.859
And then I create a text grop, grop stands for graphics object, text, the coordinates

00:13:44.859 --> 00:13:48.679
x and y, horizontal justification, and the graphics parameters.

00:13:48.679 --> 00:13:52.119
And then I call the grid.draw function to draw it.

00:13:52.119 --> 00:13:54.940
And I get this outcome.

00:13:54.940 --> 00:14:02.299
And so now, in addition, I draw the same string, but using the rich text drawing function from

00:14:02.299 --> 00:14:03.299
grid text.

00:14:03.299 --> 00:14:05.179
And so it looks like this.

00:14:05.179 --> 00:14:10.200
So now I have rich text grop, text, coordinates, hs, gp.

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:12.820
So it looks exactly the same.

00:14:12.820 --> 00:14:18.419
I put a different coordinate here, so they're in different y locations.

00:14:18.419 --> 00:14:21.219
This is at 0.7, this is 0.4.

00:14:21.219 --> 00:14:26.260
But you can actually plot them on top of each other, and they should pretty much look exactly

00:14:26.260 --> 00:14:27.260
the same.

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:29.859
And then you just draw it.

00:14:29.859 --> 00:14:31.780
OK.

00:14:31.780 --> 00:14:35.580
And that's it, actually.

00:14:35.580 --> 00:14:38.440
I want to end with one word of caution.

00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:46.140
So you may now think, oh, great, I can do anything.

00:14:46.140 --> 00:14:47.140
That is not true.

00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:56.299
You can pretty much do exactly what I showed you and not more.

00:14:56.299 --> 00:15:06.059
So the issue is that I'm not handing off the HTML to a web browser that renders it

00:15:06.059 --> 00:15:09.059
or some professional text rendering library.

00:15:09.059 --> 00:15:13.299
For technical reasons, there's just no good way right now to achieve that.

00:15:13.299 --> 00:15:17.179
So I had to write my own rendering engine from scratch.

00:15:17.179 --> 00:15:24.299
And so my approach was, OK, what are the five things that I can implement in a reasonable

00:15:24.299 --> 00:15:27.700
amount of time that really, really make a difference?

00:15:27.700 --> 00:15:30.979
And the number one is italics and bold.

00:15:30.979 --> 00:15:33.460
The number two is colors.

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:35.739
Number three is being able to change fonts.

00:15:35.739 --> 00:15:38.859
So you can change a different font if you want to.

00:15:38.859 --> 00:15:41.200
Number four is superscripts and subscripts.

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:44.200
And then number five is images.

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:47.260
So that's where I currently am.

00:15:47.260 --> 00:15:49.020
You can do a lot with that.

00:15:49.460 --> 00:15:56.219
Just this morning, I got this bug report that I was just waiting for, which listed 100 markdown

00:15:56.219 --> 00:15:58.619
features that don't currently work.

00:15:58.619 --> 00:16:00.380
Yes, I know.

00:16:00.380 --> 00:16:03.260
They don't currently work.

00:16:03.260 --> 00:16:09.979
The truth is, my vision is to increase the number of features that we support.

00:16:09.979 --> 00:16:15.000
At this point, we have a good user interface that I think will remain stable.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:20.559
And so I can now keep adding features and just eventually, at some point, certain things

00:16:20.559 --> 00:16:22.960
may work that right now don't work.

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:26.320
But anything that works now should continue to work.

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:30.719
And the R code, sorry, the R code should not change going forward.

00:16:30.719 --> 00:16:36.599
So with that, make plots with formatted text.

00:16:36.599 --> 00:16:38.400
Thank you.

00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:39.599
Thank you.

00:16:39.599 --> 00:16:40.400
You're welcome.

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:41.400
Thanks.

00:16:41.400 --> 00:16:42.400
Thanks.

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:45.400
Do you want to take some questions?

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:46.400
Yeah.

00:16:46.400 --> 00:16:47.400
Yeah.

00:16:47.400 --> 00:16:48.400
All right.

00:16:48.400 --> 00:16:49.400
Great.

00:16:49.400 --> 00:16:50.400
We have a couple minutes for questions here.

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:51.719
So let me go down the list.

00:16:51.719 --> 00:16:53.719
All right.

00:16:53.719 --> 00:16:59.760
There were a lot of questions in here that you just covered at the end, like what else

00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:00.760
is available.

00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:02.320
So I will scroll through those.

00:17:02.640 --> 00:17:08.959
Do you have any thoughts on adding shorthand markdown-ish syntactic sugar around the HTML

00:17:08.959 --> 00:17:12.439
tags for this work?

00:17:12.439 --> 00:17:15.920
I'm not sure I understand the question.

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:22.459
So the way that this whole thing works is it actually, it takes the markdown, it sends

00:17:22.459 --> 00:17:28.640
it through the regular markdown package that is part of R, which turns it into HTML, and

00:17:28.640 --> 00:17:32.040
then the HTML gets rendered.

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:38.880
So anything that you're used to doing in markdown works, in theory, as long as the

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:42.119
resulting HTML is actually supported, right?

00:17:42.119 --> 00:17:46.680
So going forward, what I need to do is I need to support more HTML features, and actually

00:17:46.680 --> 00:17:55.000
the biggest issue right now is I need to support more CSS, because that's the next big stumbling

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:58.800
block for a lot of obvious features that you would want to have.

00:17:58.800 --> 00:18:03.959
And then the markdown should just come by itself through the existing markdown package.

00:18:03.959 --> 00:18:04.959
Awesome.

00:18:04.959 --> 00:18:05.959
Thanks.

